{
  "doc_id": "7228",
  "text": "The process of testing antimicrobial activity included determination of minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) and mini-mum bactericidal concentration (MBC) which was conducted by microdilution method with resazurin [CITATION_1] . Tested plant extracts were dissolved in 10 % DMSO to a concentration of 10000 µg/mL. Sterile 96-well plates were used for making twofold serial dilutions of plant extracts with liquid media for microorganisms. The range of tested concentration was from 5000 to 78.13 µg/mL. Detailed description of this method is presented in previous paper [CITATION_2] . As positive controls we used tetracycline for bacteria and fluconazole for fungi. As negative control we used 10 % DMSO which did not influence the growth of microorganism. Growth control and sterility control were present in all tests. Also, the tests were carried out in duplicate and MICs were constant.",
